{"content":"Decision: Use asyncio.Semaphore for concurrency limiting in run_tasks

The run_tasks function caps concurrency via asyncio.Semaphore(max_concurrent). Each task wrapper does `async with sem:` before running the actual callable, so at most `max_concurrent` wrappers hold the semaphore at once. This is simpler and more idiomatic than manual counting or a work-queue pattern.

Why: asyncio.Semaphore integrates cleanly with cancellation — on CancelledError, the `async with sem.__aexit__` releases the semaphore automatically. A manual counter would require a try/finally in every wrapper, which is error-prone. Semaphore also handles the fairness question implicitly (FIFO acquisition order in CPython).","wing":"cancel-async-tasks","room":"run","importance":3,"source":"session: implementing run_tasks in run.py"}

