{"content":"Decision: Use try/except BaseException around asyncio.gather for cancellation handling

The outer try/except catches any BaseException (CancelledError, task exceptions) from the gather, then: (1) cancels all not-done runner tasks to prevent queued-but-not-started tasks from beginning execution, (2) awaits asyncio.wait(runners) to let in-flight tasks run their cleanup code, and (3) re-raises the original exception.

Why: asyncio.gather propagates cancellation to its children but does not wait for their cleanup before raising. The explicit cancel-then-wait sequence ensures that CancelledError reaches each started runner, their try/finally or async-with cleanup executes, and the semaphore is released before we re-raise. Calling .cancel() on tasks waiting to acquire the semaphore means they never enter the body — satisfying "queued tasks must not start on cancellation."","wing":"cancel-async-tasks","room":"run","importance":3,"source":"session: implementing run_tasks in run.py"}

